CollTeachThoughts: I'm an elementary school teacher and there is no way I could be a college teacher.  College kids can be so lazy!!
SculptorExplain: I'd rather teachers be compared to gardeners or guides rather than sculptors.  The verb mold makes me feel as if teachers are forcing their views onto the students (which we may sometimes do) rather than leading them through to the different answers.  This rubbed me the wrong way.
GardenerExplain: This metaphor would work better for elementary school.  While college students are still growing, I don't think of college teachers as nurturing as elementary school teachers are.
CoachExplain: Coaches are a type of teacher, albeit athletic rather than academic.  Athletes learn from their coaches and students learn from their teachers.
AppStoreExplain: Students as users have "access" to teachers.  As a store, the teachers have a plethora of "apps", or advice/knowledge, which students can use.  However, teachers aren't controlled by students like app stores are controlled by users.
TourGuideExplain: Students are touring through the country of knowledge in whatever subject they are taking.  The teachers are the experts (hopefully) and guide the tourists around.
CaptainExplain: This metaphor would work if you think of a room like a ship and the journey one of subject knowledge.  The teacher is the leader which guides the year and the students learn from this leader.
PersonalMetExplain: Coaches are a type of teacher, they offer advice, they guide, they instruct, they encourage.  Students are academic athletes who must learn from their teachers, but when they are out in the "field" (taking a test or working a job) they must rely on what they learned from their coach.  They are on their own.
ExperienceFree: I just finished my 21st year as an elementary school teacher.  I currently teach fourth grade in a public school in Orange County, California.
Comments: I didn't care for any of the metaphors oddly.  Thank you for the work!  :)

CollTeachThoughts: A college teacher is an expert in a particular subject matter. They are expected to speak well, and care about the student's education. They should be interested in their subject.
SculptorExplain: This makes the students sound completely passive, which I don't like. Education is a result of the teacher AND the student cooperating. Students have choices and different interests and aren't just molded by the teachers.
GardenerExplain: This makes student completely passive. The students-as-plants depend completely on the action of the teacher, which shouldn't be the case. It makes the process of educating overly simple, formulaic and easy, with both teacher and students not really working hard.
CoachExplain: This is a fine metaphor. There is work and agency on the part of both students and teachers. However, while success is exactly the same thing for every member of a team (winning) that isn't true for students, who can all want and receive different things from the same teacher.
AppStoreExplain: This makes teachers seem completely un-unique, as if everything they do is just a formula. It makes them sound like tools for the student to use, and I think this is almost the opposite of teaching.
TourGuideExplain: It makes the process of education sound casual and unimportant. Tourists are just visitors, and don't really take anything away when they leave a place. Students should be dedicated to learning, and plan for education to become a permanent part of who they are. A tour guide doesn't need to be much of an expert or have enthusiam.
CaptainExplain: This is a great metaphor. The captain leads the crew and makes important decisions, but doesn't do all the work. Different crew members have the same ultimate goal, but their tasks and skills can vary.
PersonalMetExplain: The best college teachers steer things in a particular direction but don't dictate every single step to take to get there. Different sailors do different things, just like different students have different talents, interests and goals. I like the idea of the class (the ship) making progress in the right direction, but having to travel and work to get there.

TourGuideExplain: This is somewhat true, in the sense that the teacher is a guide showing the tourists around and showing students what there is to see.  it is up to the students what they want to make of it and if they want to explore it further
CaptainExplain: I don't really think this is true.  A captain is in charge of a ship, andt he sailors all do what the captain says to do in order to keep the ship going.  In this metaphor, what is the ship?  I don't see any thing that it could possibly represent.  I mean in a tiny sense this is true bc the captain is in charge and the sailors are doing what he says, but a classroom shouldn't just be a dictatorship

CollTeachThoughts: The first image that comes to mind is of a man, generally older, and dignified.  He has the stereotypical tweed jacket, and smokes a pipe.  However, in my experience, more college teachers have been women than men, and they have varied greatly in age, from very young to nearing retirement.
SculptorExplain: This is the most imaginative so far.  The teacher uses his/her experience and expertise to try to mold the students into a more complete form.  However, one teacher in one class does not a finished sculpture/student make.
GardenerExplain: This one makes it sound like there is a lot less effort involved in teaching and learning than is generally the case.  I think it gives too little credit to teachers.
CoachExplain: It's not the most imaginative metaphor, but it's apt.  The teacher has gone beyond the stage in his/her life when (s)he would be an athlete/student, and is now passing on his/her wisdom and guidance to the next generation.
AppStoreExplain: This one was creative, but I found it to be false.  This would imply that a teacher has lots of different offerings, and a student can choose which subject to learn.  Maybe if the metaphor was "A university is like an app store" I would have agreed, but not in this case.
TourGuideExplain: It seemed a bit glib at first, but the more I thought about it, the more I realized that in one class/semester, a teacher really can't do more than show you the sights.  It's up to the students to decide how closely they want to look, and if they want to go deeper.
CaptainExplain: It's true that the teacher is something of an authority figure, but teachers and students generally aren't working towards the same specific goal, as would be the case with a captain and his/her sailors.
PersonalMetExplain: Like I wrote before, it's the metaphor that I feel best reflects reality.  A teacher in a single semester cannot do much more than show the sights to his/her students, just like a tour guide in an exotic city.  Hopefully, however, the students decide to dig deeper on their own, because they have been inspired to learn more.  A great teacher and a great tour guide both provide this inspiration.  I had a teacher just like this in my "Intro to Business Law" elective class, who could truly only give the absolute bare bones of the subject in our 2 hours together each week, but he showed me how fascinating the law is.  While I didn't go on to study the law, nor do I intend to, I love reading Nolo guides.

CollTeachThoughts: A person that can be relied upon for intelligence and who could be asked to answer important questions that might come up in the course of events.
SculptorExplain: It occurs to me that the role of the teacher is not to mold the student so much, as that would be more like what a mentor would do. A teacher is a bit more hands-off than that.
GardenerExplain: This makes a little bit more sense, metaphorically, compared to the other examples regarding technology or sports. I can see a natural growth analogy here.
CoachExplain: This explanation also does not quite actually fit the reality of what is going on in a class setting, and I think that most students do not consider their teacher to be like a coach.
AppStoreExplain: I think that using a technological metaphor of this sort is not a great fit for the kind of actual experience that students and teachers engaged with each other in a school setting would have.
TourGuideExplain: I don't fell like the idea of the teacher as a tour guide is accurate at all, and the students as tourists just doesn't fit or make much sense even.
CaptainExplain: I do not think that this is an appropriate way to consider the classroom experience, and there is far less of a bond between students than that of shipmates.
PersonalMetExplain: The plants have to find their own way to grow up towards the sun and receive nourishment, but the teacher can help along the way by providing extra resources or insight in order to facilitate that growth. That seems like a good way of thinking about the classroom experience.

AppStoreExplain: One has control over an app. It does what you want and results are often personalized. A college teacher is an authority who presides over you. You do what the teacher wants.
TourGuideExplain: Allan Bloom uses this metaphor in his classic "The Closing of the American Mind". One of his students called him the world's greatest tour guide. In his view, the role of the teacher is to guide the student through history, to expose the student to new ways that are not easily viewable by oneself. He uses Plato's analogy of the cave as an example.
CaptainExplain: This works. Not all the time, but works, especially for advanced classes. Here the teacher and student are on the same team, trying find the truth / reach a destination. This is how seminars are often taught. But introductory classes are different. Students cannot yet help the professor the way a sailor helps the captain.

Notes: ne of the most flattering things that ever happened to me as a teacher occurred when I received a postcard from a very good student on his first visit to Italy, who wrote, ou are not a professor of political philosophy but a travel agent.Nothing could have better expressed my intention as an educator. He thought I had prepared him to see. Then he could begin thinking for himself with something to think about. The real sensation of the Florence in which Machiavelli is believable is worth all the formulas of metaphysics ten times over. CollTeachThoughts: A man or woman who shares knowledge they have with others, through a variety of methods.  A college teacher is focused on the success of their students in understanding the material.
SculptorExplain: College professors do not change students.  Students personalities and core traits are established by college.
GardenerExplain: College teachers try to cultivate strong thinking skills.  The course a student is on is pretty set, like a plant, but as with gardening, a teacher can influence how well a student grows in their thinking.
CoachExplain: A college teacher is like a coach, they guide students to success.  They are unlike a coach in that they show more compassion, and do not bench people for poor performance.
AppStoreExplain: College teachers don't give students what the students want when they want it like an app store.  Teachers are the ones who choose what to share.
TourGuideExplain: College teachers show new things to students, like a tour guide.  One difference is that college teachers form stronger bonds with their students as the term progresses.
CaptainExplain: A class of students is like a crew.  The class and teacher share common goals, and the teacher guides the class. Not a perfect metaphor, as there can be more than one way to complete a task. On a ship, there are set ways of doing things.
PersonalMetExplain: I like this metaphor, because plants are going to be the plants they are going to be, and it is the same with students.  Some students grow to be great thinkers, others struggle. A college teacher does their best to help each student reach their best potential, like a gardener does with plants.

CollTeachThoughts: A professor who is knowledgeable in a great deal of things, but specifically in the area that he or she us teaching. Someone who is down to earth and can relate to people in general.
SculptorExplain: Sort of. Yes, students can be molded into what their teacher shares and offers, but this is only one piece of the many factors that will decide how the student grows. I agree in theory, but this metaphor is loosely stated.

TourGuideExplain: Again, I agree. A teacher is there to show students things they have never considered before. Not just regarding the tangible, but also in things that are not tangible, such as knowledge.
CaptainExplain: Sort of. However, this is loosely stated. A captain is less interested in teaching than he is involved in making sure that the sailors are doing their job. Big difference.
PersonalMetExplain: I like this one because to me, it is the most accurate depiction of the teacher - student relationship. I had a close relationship with several of my teachers and when I graduated, I felt that they had a sense of pride - that they enjoyed my college journey as much as I did.

CollTeachThoughts: A 'professor' who is usually more focused on research than academics, but will typically help you if you ask. They do not waste time coming after you if you don't make an effort first.
SculptorExplain: This is not as good because 'clay' assumes the role of the molded. The sculptor can guide, but there is a difference between sculpting your own image and guidance. Ideally, you would guide them to build their own. This analogy turns it around, slightly, and dilutes the meaning.
GardenerExplain: I'm not fond of this analogy because plants do not have the capability to respond outside of their original placement. They can grow, but they cannot change no matter how the gardener tends to it. This is an important distinction and it is that distinction which makes this not so good.
CoachExplain: Generally speaking, coaches are there to plan the route, provide guidance, and help steer those under their care in the right direction. The students (or athletes) are responsible for the physical action of making that happen. In other words, it's on them to put in the effort.
AppStoreExplain: The idea of a teacher being 'an app store' and the students being 'smartphone users' is a bit of a stretch, but it does have similar meaning to the other analogies. I'm not too fond of referring to the teacher as an 'app store' though because it implies the students simply access knowledge at will. It says nothing about the teacher's resources or longevity of the accessed information.
TourGuideExplain: Not the best, but it does have common points. The teach, in this role, acts as a guide but the students should not be labeled as 'tourists'. It implies they are there only to consume. Tourism does not necessarily mean that as it could be a learning experience, but it does sort of imply the former.
CaptainExplain: It's a little less refined than the 'coach and athlete' analogy, but it's similar. The captain simply navigates and helps keep things in line as well as provides direction. The sailors are responsible for implementing this as well as taking care of their other responsibilities. It's not quite as good of an analogy, though.
PersonalMetExplain: Again, college students are not children. By that point in their lives, they only need guidance and should be left alone to create their own paths. So, in this context, that would mean that the teacher simply coaches by giving game plans, support, and examples while the implementation is up to the students (athletes). That is, they must put forth the effort to succeed. It cannot be handed to them. Out of all the ones given, this is the most accurate representation.
Comments: Strictly speaking...you should refer to those at the college level as 'professors' :D

CollTeachThoughts: I think that a college teacher is often stuck up or self centered, at times they are unconnected to the world outside of their field.
SculptorExplain: Often times we find teachers trying to mold students into what they see fit instead of what they want to be.
GardenerExplain: I think that a teacher is a gardener who only knows about trees but is growing watermelon.
CoachExplain: They tell students what to do
AppStoreExplain: We do not get to pick what goes on its not like looking at the app store
TourGuideExplain: A tour guide who only takes you places where they like to be as opposed to showing you everything there is to see.
CaptainExplain: Teachers are the ones who dictate what occurs inside the classroom and often no matter what the students say it only matters what the teacher says.
PersonalMetExplain: I like it because it shows how teachers who are extremely knowledgeable in their field on touch on the topics they feel comfortable with. This happened to me in a Chicano study class the professor only talked about Gary Soto.
ExperienceFree: I teach high school english.

CollTeachThoughts: Someone who has a great deal of knowledge, and is interested in the success of their students. The best professors I've had have been very well versed in the topic they teach, but also expects a high level of effort from their students. A teacher who coddles students too much, or is too lenient on his/her students is generally not a great teacher.
SculptorExplain: Students are there to absorb information taught to them by the professor, so I think comparing them to an artist and a work of art is a fair comparison. Just like the artist won't be successful if their work is garbage, a professor should be judged on the success of his/her students. The students need to teacher to teach them, in order to grow and mature. Sometimes, a great teacher can change a student's life and/or career path.
GardenerExplain: A teacher provides the resources and information for students to grow as educators. Especially at the entry level, college classes are more than just absorbing information and vomiting it back to the professor in paper or exam form. The best teachers help students become successful learners, and provide them with the skills necessary to succeed, rather than simply feeding them the answers.
CoachExplain: Coaches are there to encourage players, but also help them make the best decisions and are there for tough love when it's needed. Too many college students think they can simply make up grades with extra credit, and that shouldn't be the case. Just like an athlete is to blame if they perform poorly on the field, a student is to blame if their grades aren't up to expectations.
AppStoreExplain: This makes it sound like the students can pick and choose what is important to them, which shouldn't be the case when it comes to an education. Professors should be resourceful and knowledgeable, not just there for students to take advantage of.
TourGuideExplain: In a sense, the teacher is the tour guide guiding students through a topic that is hopefully new to them, just like a tour guide would guide tourists through a new city. If the tour guide is crap, the tourists lose out on information they may be interested in.
CaptainExplain: Calling the teacher the captain and students the sailors makes it seem more like the professor is in charge, and the students are simply yes men/women who are to follow the professor's every command. I don't think a good classroom environment works like this.
PersonalMetExplain: It represents the good professors I've had so far in my college education. A good professor nurtures a student and helps him/her succeed, without coddling it or simply letting it slide by. I think the imagery of a plant represents a student's growth well, and shows that the gardener simply can't grow something without the plant, and the plant can't grow without the gardener. It's a partnership that represents success for both parties.

CollTeachThoughts: A professor who is specialized in a certain subject and teaches several different courses at a college or university.
SculptorExplain: The metaphor makes sense since teachers tend to shape students' way of thinking and help mold them into slightly different versions of themselves.
GardenerExplain: This metaphor makes sense since gardeners cultivate plants like teachers have to cultivate students to foster a positive learning experience and environment.
CoachExplain: This metaphor makes sense because like a coach with athletes working toward winning games, a teacher rallies their students to work toward goals such as exams and projects.
AppStoreExplain: I don't really understand the reference here. It just doesn't make for a metaphor that translates well to teachers and students.
TourGuideExplain: This metaphor makes sense because a tour guide illustrates and enables tourists to see and experience things that they would not otherwise without their help, similar to how a teacher guides their students to learn.
CaptainExplain: It makes sense since a professor tends to lead a class of students like a captain would lead a ship.
PersonalMetExplain: I prefer this metaphor because I believe it most accurately captures the essence of the teacher/student relationship. Students have to grow on their own, but teachers are there to foster their growth and development.

CollTeachThoughts: I think of a laid back person who is passionate about what they do. They come to class in jeans or other laid back clothes but really understand what they are teaching and want to inspire the students.
SculptorExplain: The college teacher is "molding" the students. They are preparing them for their future career and giving them the structure they need to accomplish that.
GardenerExplain: The teacher is giving the students what they need to grow as a person and grow into their future careers.
CoachExplain: I could see professor/student being very similar to the coach/athlete relationship. The athlete/student already has some experience in what they are doing but they need more guidance to learn more about the subject/sport.
AppStoreExplain: This metaphor implies the students are using the teacher. Also it implies that the students aren't really learning anything; they're just using a resource. I don't think either of those statements are true.
TourGuideExplain: I think of a tour guide of more like showing people around a place they have never seen. College students usually choose their major and know what they are getting into and probably even have prior education on the subject.
CaptainExplain: I think this statement implies that the students are simply following orders and not really learning anything new. I don't think that's true at all. In my experience a college classroom is more of a collaborative experience between teacher and student.
PersonalMetExplain: I prefer this metaphor because of how I phrased it earlier. The athlete/student is a novice or beginner in their sport/major and the coach/teacher is there to guide them to learn more about their sport/major. From my experience, classrooms were not always about taking tests and looking at a teacher perform a lecture. It was a very collaborative experience and discussion was encouraged.

CollTeachThoughts: A college teacher helps their students to think of topics from different perspectives and foster independent thinking. They also help prepare students for their chosen career.
SculptorExplain: While I agree that teachers help to mold students, I again feel that students must engage and have an active role in molding themselves as well.
GardenerExplain: This is also a good metaphor, students grow and change with their teachers aid, and each student becomes a unique individual.
CoachExplain: I definitely agree here, because with this metaphor, the students can vary in ability based on how well they listen to the coach and their individual motivation and athletic ability.
AppStoreExplain: This partially applies, but in the case the active and passive role of the metaphor is flipped. Here it seems the student actively seeks information and the teacher provides it. However, the teacher also provides information the student didn't even realize they were looking for.
TourGuideExplain: I think the student has more of an active role in learning, and the idea of being a tourist is very passive.
CaptainExplain: The teacher leads the ship and the students follow. I agree but I also think it makes the students seem like blind sheep.
PersonalMetExplain: I liked this metaphor because it emphasizes the advising and teaching role of the teacher and the individuality of the students. They are not all being molded the same or taking all of the nurturing from the teacher, but instead growing and changing in their own ways.

CollTeachThoughts: I think of someone that if they don't have a passion for teaching they can literally suck the life out of you. Your ability to learn comes from excitment, passion for the subject, and from hands on teaching stradegies.  Teachers that are not burned out and still love to teach come across as being caring and thoughtful for the process of instilling information in such a way that it shows.
SculptorExplain: This metaphor is misleading as it is saying that the teacher can shape a person into something that they aren't.  People usually have their own impressions or abilities that a teacher may not know about and unless they learn about the student they aren't molding anyone into anything.
GardenerExplain: Nurturing people is something that young people in college are not in need of.  They need guidance and helpful information to be able to make it in a very competative world and don't need nuturing. They need knowledge and need to become aware of what the real world is all about through learning.
CoachExplain: In some instances this may be true, but for the most part I think students are more like sponges that are taking in what they need to be able to thrive in a very competative society. The teaching is in the hands of the teacher and they need to get their students excited to learn.
AppStoreExplain: I don't like this metaphor, as there are many apps and people rely on their cell phones I don't think this is appropriate to try to compare mechanical devices to things that aren't necessarily a flowing changing living thing, as I believe learning is.
TourGuideExplain: I think that touring is more of a vacation and for not thinking too much about anything.  Teaching should be about curiosity and the need to take in as much information as a person can while being interested the whole time.
CaptainExplain: This is more of a metaphor for people that are learning a specific task instead of being on the same level. There is such class discrimination on board a ship where there are many levels of learning just a single task and being good at it, instead of everyone being treated the same, some loose out on learning if they are only performing a specific task.
PersonalMetExplain: I didn't think any of the metaphors were very good to try to explain teaching.

PersonalMetExplain: It just seems like the most realistic metaphor.  Coaches teach athletes what to do and they do it and same with teachers and students.

CollTeachThoughts: learned professors, keepers of all knowledge, willing to disperse it to 100's of eager students at a time
SculptorExplain: And here we are back in the "kinda, sorta, maybe" category. I heard once that Michelangelo said that his job wasn't to carve the statue from the stone, it was to simply remove all the bits that weren't the statue. That the statue was already inside. i have a friend who works in clay. When she's throwing clay, it almost feels like a battle to get the clay to go where she wants it to go. So that part could be accurate. I think a more accurate metaphor in this vein would be that the students were apprentices to the master sculptor, their teacher, and the teacher was merely teaching them how to cut away the bits of themselves that weren't their true self.
GardenerExplain: This metaphor is more appropriate than the last one. Teachers do tend to their students, nurturing them and helping them grow. They can even be the people who remove obstacles (i.e. weeds) from the students' growth. The problem is that the teacher didn't plant the students. Their parents did. their parents instilled a basic love for learning, or for subject matter,. so the students would want to grow in that area.
CoachExplain: I'll go along with this one. Athletes must be taught the rules of the game. Athletes must be taught how to play. Athletes must be taught safety. Athletes must be taught gamesmanship and fair play. Athletes must be taught everything about their sport, from the ground on up. The same can be said for philosophy, economics, higher mathematics, linguistics, physics, and all the rest.
AppStoreExplain: Absolutely not. You don't get to walk into a classroom and tell your teacher "Ok, we're going to talk about the history of the Cheerio today. Here's $1.99." The teacher sets the syllabus, chooses the subject matter, makes the choices, drives the train, steers the ship, leads the tour, decides the things. The students, far in advance, choose the courses, maybe with a little knowledge of the instructor, maybe without. It's the course they want; not the teacher.
TourGuideExplain: I think this metaphor is alright, but not great. Not even good. It implies that students are only popping in for a quick visit to knowledge or learning, before they head back home to ignorant bliss. And teachers are much more than tour guides. Tour guides show tourists the highlights only; they don't get into the nitty gritty details, the rich culture behind the village on the side of the mountain overlooking the bay. They just say "And here we have Peaceful Village #274."
CaptainExplain: I like this metaphor a lot. The teacher is at the helm, steering the ship to whatever port of call will be the most instructive. Maybe we're learning about American agriculture today, so off the boat goes to the port of Des Moines to learn about corn, wheat, and soy. Were the students shanghaied? Maybe, a bit. But for the most part, they signed on for this voyage.
PersonalMetExplain: First off, I'm enjoying the mental picture of some of my college professors as pirates, shivering their timbers with eye patches and parrots on their shoulders. I think this metaphor is the most apt because the teacher sets the course, its syllabus, and exactly what will be taught, just as a ship captain sets the course, makes daily decisions to detour here or there, and guides the shipboard operations all the while. Students pile in to a lecture hall or the cargo hold of the boat, get their marching orders, or syllabus, and off they go to the port of Des Moines.
ExperienceFree: I've taught private lessons on various musical instruments, including voice, piano, and flute, and I've tutored a variety of subjects, including English, French, math through Calculus I, basic science, philosophy, psychology, and sociology. I've also taught music classes at Vacation Bible School.
Comments: No, I think I covered everything.

CollTeachThoughts: Too many students make the mistake of sticking with their high school study methods. Most university exams will push your critical thinking and application skills. While memorization may be a component of your tests, don't rely on that method alone. Certainly you'll be required to memorize facts. However,  believe it or not, most professors expect that you'll actually follow the objectives for each chapter and lecture. Find out what those objectives are and know them by practicing them.

CollTeachThoughts: An older wiser more professional looking person who is highly educated. A person who is engaging in lectures and creative with techniques of teaching.
SculptorExplain: This one is weird sounding. I suppose because the clay is inanimate and doesn't really have an action itself. You hear people say all the time that the teacher is molding the students, but I don't personally like this metaphor. The sculptor is not teaching the clay anything and is not taking care of or nourishing the clay really.
GardenerExplain: This is another good one. Just like the gardener is caring for and feeding and watching over his plants, the college teacher is doing the same for his students.
CoachExplain: This one works very very well. The coach is guiding and teaching the athletes and has the same goal as the athletes. The coach is a mentor to them and they all work together toward the same goal.
AppStoreExplain: Again, not the best metaphor for this. The app store doesn't always support the users and the users and app store don't always collaborate very well. The app store doesn't really teach the users anything.
TourGuideExplain: This would be the best one so far that I have read here. The tour guide is the brains of the operation and is teaching and showing the tourists about everything. The guide is literally guiding them through the area or whatever it is they are touring and knows what direction to lead them in and how to get there. The college teacher does the same for the students.
CaptainExplain: This can be applied to a college teacher and the students. I suppose if both are trying to move in the same direction towards the same goal. I don't feel it is the best metaphor for this however.
PersonalMetExplain: Again I prefer this one because it appears the most common with the concept. It has the most similarities with what its being compared to.

CollTeachThoughts: I think of people who are busy with their own fields of study.  I think of piles of paper on their desks.
SculptorExplain: The teacher molds students and shows them new shapes. Students are raw materials to be shaped and guided.
GardenerExplain: The teacher tends to the students and helps them grow with daily care. The teacher provides an environment for growth.
CoachExplain: The teacher urges students to be their best. The teacher urges students to practice regularly. The teacher suggests drinking water.
AppStoreExplain: This metaphor doesn't make any sense at all. Students aren't phones and a teacher is nothing like a store.
TourGuideExplain: This seems more recreational than educational. Teachers may show new places but the students shouldn't dabble.
CaptainExplain: The teacher steers the ship. The students are mere workers and follow orders. That is all, I believe.
PersonalMetExplain: Teachers show students the way and the students follow.  Practice makes perfect and a good teacher will demonstrate this.
Comments: I feel dumber having wasted so much time on this.

CollTeachThoughts: I think usually of a guy standing at a podium in a large lecture hall. I also think about the variety of TA's who teach the smaller discussion sections
SculptorExplain: I don't think this works because it implies that all the work is done by the teacher and none by the student
GardenerExplain: I guess that's somewhat true, in that students ultimately grow on their own, but a teacher might help the process along.
CoachExplain: I don't think this fits because students can pretty much leave their team and join other teams freely
AppStoreExplain: This kind of works. The students are buying something, but what they get out of it is up to them
TourGuideExplain: This works I think. Teachers show and tell, but how much someone gets out of the experience is up to them.
CaptainExplain: I don't think this is particularly apt. Unlike a sailor, a student can get off the ship any time they want.
PersonalMetExplain: After viewing the others, I think it's the most apt. Ultimately learning is in the hands of the student and can't be forced by the teacher. They can try to help it, and they can prune the bits that don't belong, but it's still up to the student in the end.

CollTeachThoughts: A college teacher is a presenter. They don't guide you by the hand like a teacher in secondary school or in elementary school. They bring you to the information you need but your own effort is needed to digest the material.
SculptorExplain: I don't believe so in this case it applies much. Sometimes a teacher will mold students with their own values and their own perspective of the world but more often, I see them as less engaged with the students in making them follow a certain way. Although it can happen, and there is a sort of rough around the edges aspect that does apply, in my opinion.
GardenerExplain: I could see this being apt if the students are getting a lot from the experience and "growing" like a plant. But this metaphor places more of the responsibility on the teacher and in real life, it is the students who have to mature or wither, not the gardener.
CoachExplain: I don't believe this applies unless the students are in some sort of academic team or under the mentorship of a professor. But most teachers don't meet this level of leadership or guidance, at least for the majority of their students.
AppStoreExplain: I can agree with this one: the teacher is an app store, with all the information and the knowledge. The students, then based on their own focus and desire to engage, will opp in or not. Some students (users) will make sure to get the most of the experience and "pay extra" to get more out of the experience.
TourGuideExplain: I mentioned this in a previous response actually. I completely agree - the teacher is showing them the importance of wherever they are, and the tourists have the choice to either pay attention and ask more, or allow themselves to get distracted. This captures university exactly, in my opinion.
CaptainExplain: I don't see this one applying too much: most teachers in college are not leaders unless they're deans or heads of some organization. So I don't strongly disagree - but most teachers aren't looking to navigate their own ship with the students as crew. Maybe time to time, in certain settings. In general, the teacher is more like a tour boat guide.
PersonalMetExplain: Mentioned it previously but it fits perfectly because the teacher is a tour guide, showing the students what is important and what they need to focus on. A great teacher will be full of knowledge and know how to engage and keep the students interested while also educating them on what they need to know. But like a tourist, the students can either pay attention and ask questions, or challenge it or not pay attention at all. This captures university in the US very well for me, although in graduate school, this changes a bit.
ExperienceFree: I have worked as a teacher's assistant and as a tutor. I haven't taught more than 12 students at a time however.

CollTeachThoughts: Smart and willing to teach. They have a good personality and are approachable. They are respectable and care about teaching us students.
SculptorExplain: Before we entered the class we didn't know anything about the subject. We were just a unfinished block of clay. As we learned we were able to carve out pieces of the block and reveal what is hidden in it. At the end of the class it actually looks like something and has been formed.
GardenerExplain: As a teacher I am sure that you see growth in students. In this way I can see how teaching provides food for us plants so we can grow.
CoachExplain: Coaches are just there to make sure we are doing things properly. We pretty much already know what we are doing, they are just there to tweak things.
AppStoreExplain: If a teacher is like an app and we are the user we are not really learning the information. We are just using it instead.
TourGuideExplain: When you are in a tour you really don't know too much. In this way a tour guide really is a teacher.
CaptainExplain: I don't think of teachers as captains. They are not my boss. I do take orders from them, but they are there to teach me not order me around.
PersonalMetExplain: Because you start off the beginning of the class not knowing anything really, and when you are done with it you have knowledge. The block of clay has now turned into something else.

CollTeachThoughts: Someone passionate enough about their field of study that they want to share it with new generations. Alternatively, someone interested in research and willing to teach on the side to get funding
SculptorExplain: This analogy is okay. It places the responsibility for creating a beautiful work entirely in the teacher's hands which I'm not fond of. On the one hand, it encourages the teacher to really look at their class like a passion project. On the other hand, though, the students are left with the options of being cooperative clay or not I guess...?
GardenerExplain: This is just like the clay analogy. The teacher is in control here. They have all of the power. They decide whether or not the garden is beautiful or not. They do have a vested interest in helping the students "grow," but the students have no say in the matter. The just respond to stimuli
CoachExplain: This metaphor seems less strong than the sailing one because there's no easily imagined object (like a boat) tying student and teacher together. That said, here too the students and teacher share a single goal: to play well. The coach knows how to instruct their players to do so, and by succeeding in their task everyone profits
AppStoreExplain: This sort of has the opposite problem of the clay analogy. Here, the students are provided with a lot of options on what to see and how to use their findings. That's great although it's kind of a weird fit for a directed learning environment. The teacher is almost completely passive though. They can sort of proffer different ideas, I guess, but they've no control over how the students use them
TourGuideExplain: This analogy is okay. The students are given a new world to explore and the tools to explore it. Meanwhile, the teacher has the means to direct them so that they see all the important sites and no one gets lost. There's no real incentive for the teacher to perform well here though. They're not new to this area. They've seen it before, and like real life tour guides they might have some days where they just don't care if the tourists are impressed
CaptainExplain: I like this analogy because it implies that the "ship" won't go anywhere if the students are not in sync with the teacher. The teacher knows how to sail the boat, but to get moving he must teach the students what he knows. A classroom, too, is a structure without purpose if the students aren't able to haul up the anchor as it were
PersonalMetExplain: As I said in the explanation before, I think this analogy works best because it puts teacher and student in the same boat. I mean, they're literally in a boat, and they have a clear objective which is to figure out how to and then sail the thing so they get to wherever they'd like to head
ExperienceFree: I spent a few years tutoring children with learning disabilities. It was a volunteer thing, though, only a few hours a week

CollTeachThoughts: I think of a person who is intellectual, open and always learning. It is a person who loves to discover new things and enjoys a good conversation. They like tossing around ideas.

GardenerExplain: A teacher carefully cultivates the student into becoming a successful person. The teacher gives the student the things the student needs to successfully grown into a productive person just like a gardener cultivates the plant.
CoachExplain: The teacher is the person who guides the student like a coach on a sports team. He or she helps them develop skills to be a success.
AppStoreExplain: I really do not understand or relate to that analogy. I guess the teacher can be considered as having all the tools that a student needs to succeed and the students just need to pick and use the tools.
TourGuideExplain: The teacher shows the student the way and how to navigate the educational process of learning a skill. The teacher guides them through the path of learning.
CaptainExplain: The teacher is the overseer of the vessel that is education. The students are workers that help keep the ship going and they defer to the captain for help in their educational journey.
PersonalMetExplain: I like it because I believe the teacher is an overseer who guides the student in education. They help them develop the tools they need in mastering the educational system. CollTeachThoughts: An educated person who has the skillset to teach a tougher subject to a higher level classroom. A college teacher has to do more research than a typical grade school teacher, and has more freedom to their classes.
SculptorExplain: The teacher sculpts the students and helps them in their educational journeys and to be successful in their studies, as a sculptor sculpts clay into something better and more interesting than a block of clay.
GardenerExplain: A teacher is like the gardener who plants the educational seeds into the students, as flowers would in a garden, and helps them to grow to their full potential as learners.
CoachExplain: Teachers are to students as like coaches are to athletes. They help guide them in their educational path and help them to succeed in their studies, as coaches do for sports.
AppStoreExplain: This one really doesn't make sense. An app doesn't really teach the person using it, the person using it really is the one who is in control of the app and tells the app how to work and what to do.
TourGuideExplain: The teacher guides the students in their educational journeys, and the students are like the tourists on the tour and looking forward for their education and in their studies to learn more.
CaptainExplain: The teacher is like a captain guiding the students and driving their ship, and the students are like the sailors navigating the educational waters with the teacher as their guide.
PersonalMetExplain: I just like what it says. The teacher plants the seeds and helps the students grow in their college journeys.
ExperienceFree: I am in a teaching program in college, for secondary education. I have spent a lot of time in the classroom and volunteering in different programs with tutoring local high school students. I have also spent many summers teaching students in marching band programs and in charge of summer school type classrooms, as well as helping students in camp situations.

CollTeachThoughts: My college teacher is very nice person,My studies always full support.Everyone can write a thank you note on Teacher‚Äôs Day. But if you think that you have a teacher who is special, pick a random day to show your gratitude. This is not about being a geek or being a teacher‚Äôs pet. It is about showing appreciation for the way someone selflessly works hard to help students shine out as brilliant individuals
SculptorExplain: We need to disrupt the idea of having only one teacher in front of a group of students at once. With so many different learning styles and students at different places in their learning within a grade and within subjects, students and schools will benefit greatly from co-teaching models. Depending on the complexity of the topic and how the concepts are integrated into the curriculum, students might have teams of two, three, or four teachers at once. If students are learning about the recent recession, for example, they will have a math or economics specialist tag teaming with a historian.
GardenerExplain: If students are learning how to write a persuasive essay, they will benefit from having multiple language-arts specialists each provide their own unique perspective and response to students‚Äô writing and approaches. Individual teachers will not be responsible for individual students as much as the team of teachers will be responsible for the learning outcomes of each student they touch within the school day.
CoachExplain: Sometimes they will connect with a teacher online to learn something, and other times they‚Äôll work with a teacher in person to understand a concept.
AppStoreExplain: The good thing about having several teachers is that if one of them is not very good, you only have him or her for part of the day. Also, shuffling from class to class breaks up the monotony and allows for brief jokey chats in the hallway.
TourGuideExplain: I like the idea of team teaching, especially for subjects like science and math where students could benefit from more one-on-one attention from teachers. I don‚Äôt think teachers always feel like they can, singularly, meet the needs of all of their students
CaptainExplain: The notion of ‚Äúteacher‚Äù will change significantly in the future. The growing number of formal and informal learning options is causing an unbundling of the teacher role

Our imaginations gravitate toward metaphor. In the classroom, students love explanations that paint a verbal picture. In my mediation course, for example, I emphasize that options for resolution of a problem should come from the disputants themselves, not the mediator. This ensures better compliance with the terms of the agreement and creates a more durable outcome than if the mediator had suggested a solution. The question I ask my students is: ‚ÄúIf you are moving into a new house, would you rather live in a house that was built and decorated by someone else, or one you designed, built and decorated yourself?‚Äù Heads nod in comprehension, and I have saved myself five minutes of explanation about the importance of preserving the parties‚Äô right to self-determination.

CollTeachThoughts: They are frequently devoted to research and not great at working with students. This applies to a lot of them and they are frequently strict.
SculptorExplain: Teachers mold students into what they want. They can do that by teaching various things which mold the children and their lives.
GardenerExplain: Teachers have to water their students with knowledge. They feed knowledge to their students and have to keep their brains fresh and neat
CoachExplain: This doesn't have anything to do with learning and coaches don't really teach much of anything, they just train the athletes. I don't really see the similarity.
AppStoreExplain: Teachers are not like app stores. Maybe they are more like apps, though, and students are more like smartphone users. Each app is unique.
TourGuideExplain: I can see how this is a good metaphor. It makes sense since teachers teach and students listen. Teachers need to show the world and students need to learn it.
CaptainExplain: Teachers must discipline others and lead the students like a captain of a ship. Sailors, though, don't really learn anything or are taught anything.
PersonalMetExplain: I prefer this because teachers are showing a new world of knowledge to students. Thus, they are like tour guides and must show the sights to students (tourists). It makes the most sense in a knowledge-learning way. It makes the most sense because tour guides teach and tourists listen.

CollTeachThoughts: A college teacher should be knowledgeable about his or her area of expertise and should facilitate discussions rather than force-feed information.
SculptorExplain: Teachers have the power to mold their students as they see fit.
GardenerExplain: Teachers supply the tools that teach students to think and helps them to grow intellectually.
CoachExplain: Teachers offer knowledge, guidance and direction to train students to become more effective learners.
AppStoreExplain: Teachers encourage students to ask questions and make good use of their knowledge and expertise.
TourGuideExplain: An effective teacher should guide rather than dictate.This encourages students to think on their own.
CaptainExplain: Teachers should steer students' minds in the direction of passion and curiosity.
PersonalMetExplain: Gardeners supply water and some tender loving care and let nature (students) take care of the rest.

CollTeachThoughts: College teachers run the gamut but aren't usually great people-persons, and often struggle with communication.  College teachers are often better researchers or academics than they are actual teachers.
SculptorExplain: I agree partly with this.  Students have much more influence on their own molding than the quote implies.  However, in general, the educating and shaping of the students is in the hands of the professor.  The students definitely have a degree of helplessness and impotence.  Without the professor's guidance and expertise there is only so much the students can do.
GardenerExplain: This seems very similar to the sculptor/clay metaphor and I agree with it to a degree.  The growing and learning of the students is largely in the hands of the professor.  They are the ones who know where they're going and how they have to get there.  However, just like with the previous metaphor, this one fails to place onus on the students themselves.  Plants do basically nothing but sit there.  Students must be far more active in their own educations to learn or accomplish anything, regardless of the actions of the teacher.
CoachExplain: While there is definitely a little bit of truth here, since teachers and coaches aren't completely dissimilar, I don't agree with the notion that the class is necessarily like a team.  Not everyone works together, necessarily.  Classes are more loose than that, and students aren't necessarily working towards a shared goal.  True, the goal is the same, but that doesn't mean it's a shared goal.  Students are competing against one another largely, and even the teacher may be seen as an antagonist.
AppStoreExplain: I'm not even sure I understand the metaphor, and I definitely don't agree with it.  The app store in this metaphor has a passive participation in the process, while the students are placed in charge.  That's backwards and wrong.  While the students are actively involved, the teacher is the leader and isn't just a resource when and if the students feel like using it.
TourGuideExplain: This is getting a little closer to something I would agree strongly with.  I like the idea of this being a journey of sorts, with the teacher being the learned one who knows the terrain and the students coming along for the trip.  There's no requirement for the students to be passive here, but they can be if they choose to be.  And the teacher knows not only where they're going, but how they'll get there, and the details along the way.
CaptainExplain: I don't really agree with this for two primary reasons.  First, the ship metaphor implies a more complicated hierarchy, and that's not really how a class works.  In a class, there's just one leader and everyone else is a follower, as opposed to having levels of leadership.  Second of all, I never felt college classes had that feeling of everyone working towards the same goal.  Not only were things organized more loosely than that, but I felt the teacher was more of an antagonist than a leader.  It was us against him/her.
PersonalMetExplain: I think this is most illustrative of the relationship between teachers and students.  Teachers are the experts.  They know where the class is going, how they're going to get there, and the details along the way.  The students are guided there by the teacher, but they don't have to be passive (can ask questions, etc) and they don't even have to pay attention if they don't want.  The teacher would like them to follow and like them to pay attention, but that's up to the students.  The teacher is just a guide, not a taskmaster or a teammate.  it is ultimately the student's responsibility to get things out of the tour.  Also, I don't think classmates are necessarily buddies or "on the same team" or anything like that.  They're individuals who may or may not band together, but they aren't inherently interested in a shared goal, with each other or even with the teacher.  So the tour guide metaphor works there too.
